description: The preface is written “By a FRIEND,” the biblical scholar Dr. Benjamin Kennicott (iii). Kennicott was well-known for his printed sermons as well as his collations and printings of Hebrew manuscripts, including “Vetus Testamentum Hebraicum cum variis lectionibus” (“The Old Testament in Hebrew with various lessons”) in 1776. According to the Oxford Dictionary of National Biography, the “scale of [his] textual criticism (he had consulted and collated 615 manuscript versions and 52 printed editions) gave Kennicott a European reputation that transcended national and denominational boundaries.” It is very telling that Richardson asked a biblical scholar and sermon-giver to write the preface, framing his Collection as a virtuous and educational work. In the preface, Kennicott discusses the importance of secular morality in supplementing the Gospels and other religious works – the importance of man developing a “more perfect knowledge, not only of Religion, in matters relative to God, but of Virtue also, in matters relative to ourselves, and one another” (iv).
